Philippines Modeling Document¶

Prepared by Reduce.Reuse.Grow.Inc¶

Abstract¶

RRG has partnered with the Philippine Eagle Foundation (PEF) to conduct Project ReGAIN throughout the ancestral domain of the Obu-Manuvu on Mindano Island, Philippines. RRG and PEF have partnered to plant 1.5 million trees over ~1200 hectares and is planning the expansion of ~3400 hectares.
RRG and PEF have conducted forest inventories of diameter at breast height (DBH) and age. Using geospatial data (LiDAR), RRG has trained parametric regression models of forest inventory data to forecast biomass changes per hectare over the project lifetime (50 years). RRG has created a range of quartile based performance scenarios for forecasting biomass changes. In total, RRG estimates that Project ReGAIN can potentially sequester 551,657 - 2,206,629 tCo2e throughout the project lifetime.
To monitor and quantify biomass change, RRG utilizes Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) and LiDAR biomass maps provided by Google Earth Engine (GEE). RRG is able to access a broad range of temporal data and is able to establish the baseline biomass within the project area. As the stands develop, RRG will track biomass changes to train and validate forecasts.

System Overview¶

RRG's modeling system is designed to estimate carbon removals and project emissions for Project ReGAIN. RRG will leverage field data, remote sensing, and statistical learning tools within Python, Google Earth Engine (GEE) and ArcGIS Pro. The workflow is structured arround Verra's VM0047 Methodology, which provides transparent, data-driven methodologies to track biomass change and net climate benefits over time.

System Goals¶

The primary goals of the system are to:

  1. Quantify forest biomass and changes using field inventories and remote sensing data.
  2. Estimate carbon removals and project emissions (e.g., from planting, fertilizer use and leakage).
  3. Calculate net carbon benefits and project future VCUs.
  4. Evaluate the performance of machine learning models.

Data Specifications¶

Collection Period¶

The World Bank Climate Change Portal provides precipitation data for Mindanao Island. Below is a climate graph of Mindanao.

Mindanao's main rainy season is from May to December, while the dry season is from January to April. RRG will select hyperspectral imagery for study from the dry season, in an effort to

  • Reduce seasonal phenological variation
  • Select months with the lowest cloud cover

SAR and LiDAR imagery are less suceptible to the above changes, however RRG will consistently select imagery from January to April for analysis. For training models, RRG uses a median value of all available data for the year.

Coordinate Systems¶

RRG will utilize two coordinate systems. One geographic coordinate system for web based applications, the other projected coordinate system for area analysis when area quantification must be as accurate as possible:

  • Geographic Coordinate System: WGS 1984, EPSG: 4326
  • Projected Coordinate System: WGS 1984 UTM Zone 51N, EPSG: 32651

Technology Stack¶

RRG will utilize industry standard technologies for data science, remote sensing and forest monitoring. The following technology stack will be used in development and implementation of RRG's modeling system.

Remote Sensing

  • ArcGIS Pro
  • Google Earth Engine (GEE)

Data Science

Reporting

Biomass Training Dataset Collection¶

RRG aims to train field inventory models based on validated LiDAR biomass training datasets provided by NASA and the UN. RRG aims to evaluate each dataset to select the most accurate representation of the Mindano region. RRG will utilize the training datasets to add biological caps to inventory models. Furthermore, RRG will train Stocking Index (SI) values on LiDAR biomass datasets to track changes in forest structure.

def quality_mask(im):
    return im.updateMask(im.select('l4_quality_flag').eq(1)) \
             .updateMask(im.select('degrade_flag').eq(0)) \
             .updateMask(im.select('agbd').gt(0))  
year = 2020

    .filterBounds(mindanaoGeom)\
    .filterDate(f'{year}-01-01', f'{year + 1}-04-01')
abgGEDI_geom = abgDF.geometry()

Selected Biomass Source
GEDI data is sparse within the Obu-Manuvu's CADT. RRG will continually monitor GEE's database to see if GEDI data for the region becomes available. RRG will utilize GEDI data for it's current biomass estimates (see section 6.3).
Between 2010 sources, old growth forests throughout the region range from 177 - 214 tC/ha. For inventory model training, RRG has selected a biological cap ~ 200 tC/ha. For SI model training, RRG utilizies the 2010 biomass dataset provided by NASA.

Field Inventories¶

PEF has conducted initial field inventories of species to be planted. GEE datasets do not provide age data, however RRG can use the inventory data to forecast carbon removals throughout the project lifetime. RRG first converts DBH to mass (t) by utilizing allometric equations. RRG then models age and biomass to predict potential biomass of the site throughout the project lifetime. The following equation describes the model: $$ \text{Biomass (kg/tree)} = f(\text{Age}) $$

Allometric Conversion
To convert DBH into aboveground weight (kg), RRG has conducted a thorough analysis of allometric equations for the Mindanao region. RRG chose the most conservative allometric equation provided by Kenzo, et al.

def ql(data):
    df = data.iloc[:, [0,1]]
    x = df.iloc[:,0]
    y = df.iloc[:,1]
    xName = df.columns[0]
    yName = df.columns[1]
    #Statistics
    df.corr()
    spearman_corr = x.corr(y, method='spearman')
    print('Spearman Correlation:', spearman_corr)
    # Calculate standard deviations
    std_x = df[xName].std()
    std_y = df[yName].std()
    # Create text for standard deviation
    textstrx = f'Standard Deviation of\n{xName}: {std_x:.2f}'
    textstry = f'Standard Deviation of\n{yName}: {std_y:.2f}'
    props = dict(boxstyle='round', facecolor='grey', alpha=0.5)
    # statistical graphs
    sns.set_theme()
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(10, 8))  
    axs = axs.flatten() 
    #Scatter plot distribution
    sns.scatterplot(x = f"{xName}", y = f"{yName}", data = df, alpha=0.5, color='purple', ax=axs[0])
    axs[0].set_title('Scatter Plot')
    axs[0].set_xlabel(f'{xName}')
    axs[0].set_ylabel(f'{yName}')
    #heatmap of correlations
    sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', ax=axs[1], cbar=True, cbar_kws={"label": "Correlation Coefficient"})
    axs[1].set_title('Correlation Heatmap')
    # hist plot
    sns.histplot(df[f"{xName}"], kde=True, color="darkgreen", ax=axs[2])
    axs[2].set_title(f'Distribution of {xName}')
    axs[2].set_xlabel(f'{xName}')
    axs[2].text(0.98, 0.95, textstrx, transform=axs[2].transAxes, fontsize=8,
        verticalalignment='top', bbox=props, horizontalalignment='right')
    sns.histplot(df[f"{yName}"], kde=True, color="darkgreen", ax=axs[3])
    axs[3].set_title(f'Distribution of {yName}')
    axs[3].text(0.98, 0.95, textstry, transform=axs[3].transAxes, fontsize=8,
        verticalalignment='top', bbox=props, horizontalalignment='right')
    axs[3].set_xlabel(f'{yName}')
    fig.suptitle(f'Distribution of {xName} and {yName}')
    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.92], pad=1.0)
    plt.show()

Model Design¶

RRG has created a parametric regression modeling function to be used for each dataset. The function utilizes 2nd Polynomial, 3rd Polynomial, Logarithmic, Power and Chapman-Richard's equations to predict biomass given age. Included in the function are statistical metrics including R2, RMSE and MPE to track model quality.

In [67]:
def model(data):
    df = data.copy()
    x = df.iloc[:, 0]
    y = df.iloc[:, 1]
    xName = df.columns[0]
    yName = df.columns[1]
    # PARAMETRIC MODELING
    #linear modeling/polynomial 
    results = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName}', data=df, weights=df['weights']).fit()
    poly2 = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName} + I({xName}**2)', data=df, weights=df['weights']).fit()
    poly3 = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName} + I({xName}**2) + I({xName}**3)', data=df, weights=df['weights']).fit()
    #non linear with including log, power, exponential, chapman richards
    def power(x, a,b):
        return a * x**b
    powerModel = Model(power)
    pParams = powerModel.make_params(a=0.5, b=1)
    pParams['a'].set(min=0)
    pParams['b'].set(min=0)
    pResult = powerModel.fit(df[f'{yName}'], pParams, x =df[f'{xName}'], weights=df['weights'])
    def CR(x, a, b, c):
        return a * (1 - np.exp(-b * x))**c
    CRModel = Model(CR)
    CRParams = CRModel.make_params(a=(df[f'{yName}'].max()), b=0.03, c=2)
    CRParams['a'].set(min=0)
    CRParams['b'].set(min=0)
    CRParams['c'].set(min=0)
    CRResult = CRModel.fit(df[f'{yName}'].values, CRParams, x=df[f'{xName}'].values, nan_policy='omit', weights=df['weights'])
    def log(x, a, b):
        return a * np.log(x) + b
    logModel = Model(log)
    lParams = logModel.make_params(a=0.5, b=1)
    lResult = logModel.fit(df[f'{yName}'], lParams, x=df[f'{xName}'], nan_policy='omit', weights=df['weights'])
    
    # QUICK LOOK TO COMPARE MODEL OUTCOMES
    # Mean Percentage Error
    def mean_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred):
        y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
        nonzero_mask = y_true != 0
        if not np.any(nonzero_mask):
        # All y_true are zero, can't compute MPE
            return np.nan
        mpe = np.mean((y_true[nonzero_mask] - y_pred[nonzero_mask]) / y_true[nonzero_mask]) * 100
        return mpe
    def evaluate_model(name, y_true, y_pred, formula):
        return {
        'Model': name,
        'Formula': formula,
        'R²': r2_score(y_true, y_pred),
        'RMSE': np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)),
        'MPE': mean_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred)
    }
    results_list = []
    y_pred_linear = results.predict(df)
    formula_linear = f"{yName} = {results.params['Intercept']:.3f} + {results.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Linear', df[yName], y_pred_linear, formula_linear))
    y_pred_poly2 = poly2.predict(df)
    formula_poly2 = (f"{yName} = {poly2.params['Intercept']:.3f} + "
                 f"{poly2.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName} + "
                 f"{poly2.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)']:.3f} * {xName}²")
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Polynomial (2nd)', df[yName], y_pred_poly2, formula_poly2))
    y_pred_poly3 = poly3.predict(df)
    formula_poly3 = (f"{yName} = {poly3.params['Intercept']:.3f} + "
                 f"{poly3.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName} + "
                 f"{poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)']:.3f} * {xName}² + "
                 f"{poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 3)']:.3f} * {xName}³")
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Polynomial (3rd)', df[yName], y_pred_poly3, formula_poly3))
    y_pred_log = lResult.eval(x=df[xName])
    aL = lResult.params['a'].value
    bL = lResult.params['b'].value
    formula_log = f"{yName} = {aL:.3f} * ln({xName}) + {bL:.3f}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Logarithmic', df[yName], y_pred_log, formula_log))
    y_pred_power = pResult.eval(x=df[xName])
    aP = pResult.params['a'].value
    bP = pResult.params['b'].value
    formula_power = f"{yName} = {aP:.14f} * {xName} ^ {bP:.3f}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Power', df[yName], y_pred_power, formula_power))
    y_pred_CR = CRResult.eval(x=df[xName])
    aCR = CRResult.params['a'].value
    bCR = CRResult.params['b'].value
    cCR = CRResult.params['c'].value
    formula_CR = f"{yName} = {aCR:.3f} * (1 - exp(-{bCR:.3f} * {xName})) ^ {cCR:.3f}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Chapman-Richards', df[yName], y_pred_CR, formula_CR))
    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(results_list)
    metrics_df = metrics_df.sort_values(by='R²', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
    

    #GRAPH RESULTS
    # Create x values
    x_vals = np.linspace(1.3 * df[xName].min(), 1.3 * df[xName].max(), 200)
    # Scatter plots of original data
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 6))
    axs[0].scatter(df[xName], df[yName], label='Inventory Data', color='lightblue', alpha=0.6, s=20)
    axs[1].scatter(df[xName], df[yName], label='Inventory Data', color='lightblue', alpha=0.6, s=15)
    # Linear
    y_vals_linear = results.params['Intercept'] + results.params[xName] * x_vals
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_linear, label='Linear', color='blue', linestyle='-')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_linear, label='Linear', color='blue', linestyle='-')
    # Polynomial 2nd degree
    y_vals_poly2 = (poly2.params['Intercept'] 
                + poly2.params[xName] * x_vals 
                + poly2.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)'] * x_vals**2)
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly2, label='Polynomial (2nd)', color='green', linestyle='--')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly2, label='Polynomial (2nd)', color='green', linestyle='--')
    # Polynomial 3rd degree
    y_vals_poly3 = (
    poly3.params['Intercept'] 
    + poly3.params[xName] * x_vals 
    + poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)'] * x_vals**2 
    + poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 3)'] * x_vals**3
    )
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly3, label='Polynomial (3rd)', color='darkgreen', linestyle=':')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly3, label='Polynomial (3rd)', color='darkgreen', linestyle=':')
    # Power
    aP = pResult.params['a'].value
    bP = pResult.params['b'].value
    y_vals_power = aP * x_vals**bP
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_power, label='Power', color='purple', linestyle='-.', linewidth = 2)
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_power, label='Power', color='purple', linestyle='-.', linewidth = 2)
    # Logarithmic (only valid for x_vals > 0)
    x_vals_log = x_vals[x_vals > 0]
    y_vals_log = lResult.params['a'].value * np.log(x_vals_log) + lResult.params['b'].value
    axs[0].plot(x_vals_log, y_vals_log, label='Logarithmic', color='orange', linestyle='--')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals_log, y_vals_log, label='Logarithmic', color='orange', linestyle='--')
    # Chapman-Richards
    aCR = CRResult.params['a'].value
    bCR = CRResult.params['b'].value
    cCR = CRResult.params['c'].value
    y_vals_CR = aCR * (1 - np.exp(-bCR * x_vals))**cCR
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_CR, label='Chapman-Richards', color='brown', linestyle='-.')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_CR, label='Chapman-Richards', color='brown', linestyle='-.')
    # Final plot formatting
    axs[0].set_ylim(-5, (1.2*df[xName].max()))
    axs[0].set_xlim(0,(1.2*df[xName].max()))
    axs[1].set_ylim(-.01, .4)
    axs[1].set_xlim(0,50)
    for ax in axs.flat:
        ax.set(xlabel='Age', ylabel='Biomass per Tree (tC)')
    plt.suptitle('Predicting Biomass per Tree Given Inventory Data')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    return metrics_df

Copying the Dataset and Adding Dataset Weights
Below RRG uses the inventory dataset to model biomass for each planting composition. RRG copies the inventory dataset and produces three identical datasets for modeling (Agroforestry, Instance 2 modeled together). RRG then adds weights to all data points under the respective maximum single tree biomass. This ensures the models are trained on the most conservative data.

Quantifying Uncertainty with Quartile-Based Performance Scenarios¶

RRG understands the complexity of forest restoration and the need for a sliding scale of performance biomass outcomes. RRG trained the models with the understanding that project activities cannot outpreform existing old-growth forests in biomass growth. In conjunction, RRG needs to estimate worse case scenarios where poor site conditions (competing vegetation, dry) or catastrophic risk events influence growth. So, RRG has prepared quartile based scaling scenarios for ex-ante predictions of carbon removals:

  • Low Performing Models (25%, delta tC/ha = 50)
  • Mid Performing Models (50-75%, delta tC/ha = 100-150)
  • High Performing Models (100%, delta tC/ha = 200)

Leakage¶

Mindanao Island has available data regarding historical grower records and illegal logging rates. However, there is no data available for the Obu-Manuvu people. RRG can see from remote sensing that farms throughout the project zone are quite small and are believed to be subsistence farms.
Moving into the future, RRG and PEF will complete the FPIC process and hold local farmer interviews to determine foregone production within the project area. Project activities will not displace any farms within the project area. PEF aims to mitigate leakage into the surrounding region by employing these farmers and providing them with an alternate, sustainable livelihood.
Until the FPIC process occurs, RRG has decided to implement the default leakage deductions set out in the Verra Standard, v4.7. These deductions are taken from the gross Co2e removals and are 15% from activity shifting leakage and 10% from market shifting leakage.
RRG will ultimately use the VM0054 ARR Leakage module to calculate leakage. This module first estimates leakage by calculating production (based on grower records), an anticipated amount of new land brought into production and the determination of the change in carbon stock due to this land change. Cumulatively, the following equation describes how RRG will quantify leakage.

For ex-ante estimations, leakage must be quantified in tCo2. To do this with the default 25% rate, RRG takes 25% of total Co2e removals from each performance scenario.

In [78]:
def leak(mass):
    metric = mass * 0.25
    return(metric)

Remote Sensing Performance Benchmark¶

Modeling of SI at Biomass¶

RRG has compared a range of stocking indices (SI) including SAR HV and NDFI to monitor biomass accumulation. RRG has initially chosen SAR imagery to model biomass.

Model Design¶

It's important to note that HV (db) index values are negative. Because of this, not all parametric models will work. Users may employ log scaling, however RRG has chosen to compare linear, polynomial, support vector and gradient boosted regression models.

In [18]:
def SI_model(data):
    df = data.copy()
    x = df.iloc[:, 0]
    y = df.iloc[:, 1]
    xName = df.columns[0]
    yName = df.columns[1]
    # PARAMETRIC MODELING
    #linear modeling/polynomial 
    results = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName}', data=df).fit()
    poly2 = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName} + I({xName}**2)', data=df).fit()
    poly3 = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName} + I({xName}**2) + I({xName}**3)', data=df).fit()
    # QUICK LOOK TO COMPARE MODEL OUTCOMES
    # Mean Percentage Error
    def mean_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred):
        y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
        nonzero_mask = y_true != 0
        if not np.any(nonzero_mask):
        # All y_true are zero, can't compute MPE
            return np.nan
        mpe = np.mean((y_true[nonzero_mask] - y_pred[nonzero_mask]) / y_true[nonzero_mask]) * 100
        return mpe
    def evaluate_model(name, y_true, y_pred, formula):
        return {
        'Model': name,
        'Formula': formula,
        'R²': r2_score(y_true, y_pred),
        'RMSE': np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)),
        'MPE': mean_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred)
    }
    results_list = []
    y_pred_linear = results.predict(df)
    formula_linear = f"{yName} = {results.params['Intercept']:.3f} + {results.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Linear', df[yName], y_pred_linear, formula_linear))
    y_pred_poly2 = poly2.predict(df)
    formula_poly2 = (f"{yName} = {poly2.params['Intercept']:.3f} + "
                 f"{poly2.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName} + "
                 f"{poly2.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)']:.3f} * {xName}²")
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Polynomial (2nd)', df[yName], y_pred_poly2, formula_poly2))
    y_pred_poly3 = poly3.predict(df)
    formula_poly3 = (f"{yName} = {poly3.params['Intercept']:.3f} + "
                 f"{poly3.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName} + "
                 f"{poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)']:.3f} * {xName}² + "
                 f"{poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 3)']:.3f} * {xName}³")
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Polynomial (3rd)', df[yName], y_pred_poly3, formula_poly3))
    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(results_list)
    metrics_df = metrics_df.sort_values(by='R²', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
    #GRAPH RESULTS
    # Create x values
    x_vals = np.linspace(1.3 * df[xName].min(), 1.3 * df[xName].max(), 200)
    # Scatter plots of original data
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.scatter(df[xName], df[yName], label='GEE Data', color='lightblue', alpha=0.6, s=20)
    # Linear
    y_vals_linear = results.params['Intercept'] + results.params[xName] * x_vals
    plt.plot(x_vals, y_vals_linear, label='Linear', color='blue', linestyle='-')
    # Polynomial 2nd degree
    y_vals_poly2 = (poly2.params['Intercept'] 
                + poly2.params[xName] * x_vals 
                + poly2.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)'] * x_vals**2)
    plt.plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly2, label='Polynomial (2nd)', color='green', linestyle='--')
    # Polynomial 3rd degree
    y_vals_poly3 = (
    poly3.params['Intercept'] 
    + poly3.params[xName] * x_vals 
    + poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)'] * x_vals**2 
    + poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 3)'] * x_vals**3
    )
    plt.plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly3, label='Polynomial (3rd)', color='darkgreen', linestyle=':')
    # Final plot formatting
    plt.ylim(-1, (1.2*df[yName].max()))
    plt.xlim((1.2* df[xName].min()), (1.2*df[xName].max()))
    plt.xlabel('HV Index Value (dB)')
    plt.ylabel('Biomass per ha (tC)')
    plt.title('Predicting Biomass per Hectare Given SAR HV Data')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    return metrics_df

def xgBoost(data):
    df = data.copy()
    x = df.iloc[:, 0].to_numpy().reshape(-1, 1)   # <-- convert to numpy array first
    y = df.iloc[:, 1].to_numpy()
    xName = df.columns[0]
    yName = df.columns[1]

    # Split data into train/test (80% train, 20% test)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
    # Create XGBoost regressor
    model = xgb.XGBRegressor(
        objective='reg:squarederror',
        n_estimators=1000,
        max_depth=10,
        learning_rate=0.001,
        random_state=42
    )

    # Train model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predict on test set
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Evaluate
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    print(f'R²: {r2:.3f}')
    print(f'RMSE: {rmse:.3f}')
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred, alpha=0.5, edgecolors='k')
    plt.plot([y_test.min(), y_test.max()], [y_test.min(), y_test.max()], 'r--')
    plt.xlabel('Actual Biomass')
    plt.ylabel('Predicted Biomass')
    plt.title('XGBoost Predicted vs Actual Biomass')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

def svr(data):
    df = data.copy()
    x = df.iloc[:, 0].to_numpy().reshape(-1, 1)   # <-- convert to numpy array first
    y = df.iloc[:, 1].to_numpy()
    xName = df.columns[0]
    yName = df.columns[1]

    # Split data into train/test (80% train, 20% test)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
    
    model = SVR(kernel='rbf', C=10000, gamma='scale', epsilon=1)

    # Train model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predict on test set
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Evaluate
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    print(f'R²: {r2:.3f}')
    print(f'RMSE: {rmse:.3f}')
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred, alpha=0.5, edgecolors='k')
    plt.plot([y_test.min(), y_test.max()], [y_test.min(), y_test.max()], 'r--')
    plt.xlabel('Actual Biomass')
    plt.ylabel('Predicted Biomass')
    plt.title('XGBoost Predicted vs Actual Biomass')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

SAR HV Backsplatter¶

SAR backscatter images are representations of the microwave portion of the electromagnetic spectrum. SAR data is commonly used for detecting forest changes and is less suceptible to seasonal variations. The following equation sums the model: $$ \text{Biomass} = f(\text{SAR HV}) $$ $$ \text{where Biomass = WCMC Aboveground and Belowground Biomass} $$

def applyQualityMask(image):
    # Assuming 'MSK' is the data quality mask band
    msk = image.select('qa')
    # Mask out pixels with value 50 (commonly water/invalid in ALOS PALSAR)
    mask = msk.neq(50)
    masked_image = image.updateMask(mask)
    return masked_image
def convertToGammaNaught(image):
    # Convert DN to gamma naught (γ₀) in decibels
    gamma_naught = image.pow(2).log10().multiply(10).subtract(83)
    return gamma_naught
collection = (
    palsar
    .map(convertToGammaNaught)  # Convert DN to gamma naught
    .map(applyQualityMask)
)
palsarImage = collection.median().clip(SIGeom)

Model Selection
It's evident RRG's dataset is noisy and results in low R2 values. When comparing model results and curve shapes, RRG chose the 2nd Polynomial equation for export due to it's high end (150-200ha) biomass estimates. Moving into the future, RRG will refine these models.

In [29]:
def biomass_HV(HV):
    biomass = 327.932 + 25.596 * HV + 0.504 * HV**2 
    return(biomass)

Baseline Biomass¶

RRG will utilize time series analysis to determine the baseline conditions of the project sites at three distinct time periods from t=-8, t=-3, and t=0. This corresponds to 2015, 2020 and 2023.

Using SAR Data¶

RRG utilized the Jaxa yearly mosaic going back to 2010 for the training models. However, this dataset does not provide data beyond 2020. Despite this, Jaxa provides multiple datasets with more up to date data. RRG will utilize this dataset for baseline biomass analysis.

Biomass Conversion and Scaling
The SAR training models are meant to predict biomass at the hectare level. However, each SAR pixel is only 25m x 25 or 0.0625 hectares. Therefore, RRG scaled each biomass prediction by 0.0625 to get the biomass per pixel

Model Performance Discussion¶

RRG can estimate historical biomass and future biomass of the project area utilizing SI and machine learning. RRG understands that model performance varies between datasets and that improvements can be made. Moving into the future, RRG will include model updates for the following categories:

  • Field Inventory Models
    • Model Results
      • R2 values near 0 due to LiDAR training weights
      • High RMSE due to LiDAR training weights
      • Negative MPE indicating underfitting due to LiDAR training weights
    • Model Upgrades
      • Quartile Regression to compare to parametric regression with training weights
      • Add additional datapoints with PEF field data
  • SI/Biomass Models
    • Model Results
      • R2 values near 0.33 due to dataset noise
      • High RMSE due to dataset noise
      • Negative MPE indicating underfitting
    • Model Upgrades
      • Additional SI predictors including NDFI, LiDAR Canopy Height
      • More complex models including multiple linear regression, SVR, XGB Boost improvements

RRG understands the importance of accurate remote sensing and field monitoring systems to quantify biomass changes throughout the project lifetime. This document will serve as a living library and will be updated as RRG makes upgrades.
